  <h2 id="scanning">Speed Reading and Scanning Techniques</h2>
  <p>At N1 level, reading every word carefully is too slow. You need strategic scanning:</p>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #f0f9ff; border: 2px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #2563eb;">📖 Read Questions First</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Always read the questions BEFORE the passage. This tells you exactly what information to look for, so you can skim irrelevant sections quickly.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border: 2px solid #22c55e; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #16a34a;">🔍 Paragraph First Sentences</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Read the first sentence of each paragraph to get the structure. Most Japanese academic writing follows a topic-sentence pattern. This gives you a mental map before diving in.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fefce8; border: 2px solid #eab308; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #ca8a04;">⚡ Signal Word Scanning</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Scan for しかし (however), つまり (in other words), 一方 (on the other hand), したがって (therefore). These mark where the argument shifts or concludes.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background: #eff6ff; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem 1.2rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <strong>🔑 Key Signal Words for N1 Reading:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem;">
      <li><strong>しかし / ところが / だが</strong> — Contrast (the next part is often the author's real opinion)</li>
      <li><strong>つまり / 要するに / すなわち</strong> — Summary (rephrases the main point)</li>
      <li><strong>したがって / そのため / ゆえに</strong> — Conclusion (the result or argument)</li>
      <li><strong>例えば / 具体的には</strong> — Example (supporting detail, not the main point)</li>
      <li><strong>〜ではないだろうか</strong> — Rhetorical question (the author's opinion disguised as a question)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="tricky-questions">How to Handle Tricky Questions</h2>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #dc2626;">🪤 Common Traps</strong>
      <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <li>Options that are true but do not answer the question</li>
        <li>Options with one wrong word changing the meaning</li>
        <li>Extreme language (必ず, 絶対) when the passage is more nuanced</li>
        <li>Confusing the author's opinion with a quoted opposing view</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border: 1px solid #86efac; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #16a34a;">✅ How to Avoid Them</strong>
      <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <li>Re-read the specific question before choosing</li>
        <li>Find the exact sentence in the passage that supports your answer</li>
        <li>Eliminate options with absolute language if the passage hedges</li>
        <li>Track who is speaking — author vs. quoted person</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

